events.description: Job openings fell to a five-year low in December.
Reflected the most January job cuts since 2009.
Claims were sharply above expectations to a two-month high.
Private-sector job growth fell well short of expectations.
Treasury maintained guidance favoring short-term bills over longer-dated bonds.

facts.fact_text: The yield on the 10-year US Treasury note fell to 4.2% on Thursday.

evidences.evidence_text: The yield on the 10-year US Treasury note fell further to the 4.2% mark on Thursday, the lowest in nearly three weeks

facts.fact_text: JOLTS job openings fell to a five-year low in December.

evidences.evidence_text: The JOLTS showed that job openings fell to a five-year low in December

facts.fact_text: Initial jobless claims reached a two-month high.

evidences.evidence_text: initial jobless claims were sharply above expectations to a two-month high

claims.claim_text: Markets are pricing in a first rate reduction in June and a second in September.
claims.author: markets

evidences.evidence_text: markets still pricing in a first reduction in June and a second potentially in September

claims.claim_text: Soft labor data supports the outlook of multiple rate cuts by the Federal Reserve.

evidences.evidence_text: a batch of soft labor data supported the outlook of multiple rate cuts by the Federal Reserve this week

claims.claim_text: The US Treasury is favoring short-term bills to manage borrowing costs.
claims.author: US Treasury

evidences.evidence_text: favouring a greater share of short-term bills over longer-dated bonds in an effort to manage borrowing costs amid elevated interest rates

evidence.evidence_text: The run of weaker labor data reinforced bets on multiple Federal Reserve rate cuts this year
